Git Basics & Commands (README Notes)
What is Git

Git is a distributed version control system used to track changes in files and collaborate on projects. It allows developers to save versions of their work, revert to previous versions, and work with others without overwriting each other’s changes.

Git stores project history using commits, which are snapshots of the project at specific points in time.

Important Git Definitions
Repository (Repo)

A repository is a folder that Git tracks. It contains project files and a hidden .git directory where Git stores version history.

Example:

my-project/
 ├── index.html
 ├── script.js
 └── .git/
Commit

A commit is a saved snapshot of the project. Each commit records changes and includes a message describing what was modified.

Example commit message:

Added login page and fixed navigation bug
Branch

A branch is a separate version of the project where changes can be made without affecting the main version.

The default branch is usually called main or master.

Example:

main
feature-login
bug-fix-navbar
Clone

Cloning downloads a copy of a remote repository to your local computer.

Example command:

git clone https://github.com/user/project.git
Push

Push uploads local commits to a remote repository.

Example:

git push origin main
Pull

Pull downloads updates from the remote repository and merges them with your local version.

Example:

git pull origin main
Merge

A merge combines changes from one branch into another branch.

Example:

feature-login → main
Basic Git Workflow

A typical Git workflow looks like this:

Edit files
↓
git add
↓
git commit
↓
git push
Common Git Commands
Initialize a Repository

Creates a new Git repository in the current folder.

git init
Clone a Repository

Downloads a repository from a remote server.

git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git
Check Repository Status

Shows which files are modified or staged.

git status
Add Files to Staging Area

Stages files so they can be committed.

Add one file:

git add filename.txt

Add all files:

git add .
Commit Changes

Saves staged changes to the Git history.

git commit -m "Added new feature"
View Commit History

Shows all commits in the repository.

git log

Short version:

git log --oneline
Create a Branch

Creates a new branch.

git branch feature-branch
Switch Branches

Move to a different branch.

git checkout feature-branch

or newer command:

git switch feature-branch
Merge Branches

Combine another branch into the current branch.

git merge feature-branch
Push Changes

Uploads commits to the remote repository.

git push origin main
Pull Updates

Downloads the newest changes from the remote repository.

git pull origin main
Git in Cybersecurity / Forensics

In cybersecurity competitions, Git can be analyzed to recover hidden information such as:

deleted files

hidden flags

previous versions of code

commit messages

old branches

Useful commands for investigation:

git log
git log -p
git show <commit>
git diff
git fsck

These commands help investigators see historical changes in a repository.

Summary
Git is a powerful tool that allows developers to:
track changes in files
collaborate with others
manage different versions of a project
recover older versions of code
Understanding Git commands and repository structure is important for both software development and cybersecurity analysis.
